Title_Description: loading realm objects on the ui thread in [using realm across threads]( the documentation states that the only rule to using realm across threads is to remember that realm realmobject or realmresults instances cannot be passed across threads.in android (and any other gui application) its a big no-no to load/query data on the ui thread. when using sqlite the convention is to create an asynctask in your activity that populates the ui elements with data from the sqlite database.with realm the documentation actively advises against passing results to from a background thread to a ui thread (as its considered across a thread). i have seen the [realmconcurrencyexample]( but unfortunately it uses two background (non-ui threads). in [realmgridviewexample]( the query to the realm database is made on the ui thread.my questions about this are- is loading realm data on the ui thread okay? are there any disadvantages to doing so?- if its not okay to load realm data on the ui thread how should i populate my ui elements with realm data when potentially large queries are involved?- would it be possible to update the documentation to explain to developers whether its okay to load on the ui thread? i would think many other android developers would be concerned about executing a realm call on the ui thread without knowing the ramifications.by the way you guys have a great product here. i cant wait to see how it grows.

Title_Description: deleted items still present in query results ive encountered a data consistency issue when deleting on a background thread from a different context. i have a list of items and clicking on an item will open a secondary activity. if the item is deleted                                                                                                                         on a background thread on this secondary activity it will still show on the list back in the first activity. the list data is reloaded inside onresume and the list activity registers with realm for change events. even if the data is reloaded explicitly the deleted item is still present in the result set.the deleted item will only be removed from the result set if you either do a write operation (insert a new element into the list) or restart the app. simply sending the app to the background and resuming it again doesnt solve the issue. the app needs to be force stopped and then restarted. deleting the item from a background thread on the list activity will remove the item from the list. deleting the item on the main thread from the secondary activity will also remove the item from the list. deleting the item on a background thread on the secondary activity will _not_ remove the item from the list.ive modified my sample realm project to replicate the issueonce compiled the app is named realm.io. its very simple to reproduce the issue. just click on add item menu option to add an item. click on the item to open the secondary activity and click on the delete  button. once the secondary activity finishes the first activity will still show the deleted item on the list. if you click on add item once again the deleted item will be removed and a new item will be inserted on the list. the deleted item can also be removed by pushing the app to the background swiping it away from the recent apps list and starting it over.

Title_Description: realmconfiguration.allowwritesonuithread() after a discussion in 2952 we came to the conclusion that given how async queries work it is impossible to mix synchronous writes on the ui thread and async queries and still guarantee a consistent view for all realmresults before we changed syncifneeded to only happen on looper threads the problem also existed but instead manifested itself as all async queries would convert to run directly on the ui instead which broke the api contract given by findallasync()after we changed it the problem became worse though as now async realmresults would advance_read (due to the commit) but detached row accessors might appear due to us not calling syncifneeded. this could result in unexpected crashes.this race condition is impossible to avoid so i suggest the following changes2952 will introduce a log warning if you mix those async queries and sync writes. this will be shipped in 1.0.1in 1.1.0 or later  we introduce a new realmconfiguration.allowwritesonuithread() option. the default value is true to avoid breaking changes but it will make it possible for people to it on and fix their code.in 2.0 we change the default value from true to false so the default behaviour is that writes on the ui thread is not allowed.
Name: design-required| pipeline-idea-backlog| t-enhancement

Title_Description: async reads and writes should not use same thread pool   use case   reported by a user starting an app that runs a large number of synchronization jobs on startup (20+). goal is to have something to show in the ui as fast as possible using async queries but currently there can be a large delay before data is available.    problem   we only have one realm thread pool for both async reads and writes. as realm write transactions are blocking across threads if  more write jobs than available processors exists the thread pool will effectively be serialized and act as a single-threaded pool as realm core will block all parallel write jobs running. in the worst case where writes are scheduleded before queries the queries could be blocked for a long time.    solution   split the current thread pool into two 1 for reads and 1 for writes. the one for writes just needs to be a single-threaded pool as multiple threads doesnt make sense. this would mean that async queries always have a chance to run.
Name: t-enhancement

Title_Description: realmlist<integer / string / ... dear realm-team   im really impressed by realm and i do like the way youre providing support and solutions on github so and ggroups  i like working with realm - however there are three really big drawbacks for me  1) no model-instantiation by = new ... - i know youre on it. i cant wait for this  do we have to wait for the whole json-upgrade or will there be an earlier release providing this feature?  2) no model-passing across threads. thats hindering all the great benefits of eventbus and android priority job queue. but i read that it will be possible in the further versions and im looking forward on this.  3)   the reason for this issue   in my model class im allowed to have primitive fields as well as object fields of objects that extend realmobject. but im not allowed to have a field type like realmlist<integer or realmlist<string. however it is possible to work around this by    it works but its _really_ ugly and should be unnecessary in my opinion. is there any improvement planned regarding this?  thanks again for your great work - im glad realm helps me developing my app    ---   related prs  - [ ] api design (4165)  - [ ] implementation (5031)

Title_Description: update encryption docs  describe your problem or use case the encryption docs only states that aes-256 is used and a 512-bit key is required. this is confusing to some of us not too familiar with encryption. it looks like a 512-bit key is required because 256-bits are used by aes and the rest by hmac.   describe the solution youd like this [solution]( was beneficial to figuring out how realm actually uses the key. it would be nice for the encryption docs to be a little more clear on how realm handles encryption for the different projects that require more info on security and encryption.  from contributor we use aes-256 which takes a 256 bit key not bytes ... since a byte is 8 bit we thus take a 512 (64x8) bit key. the first 256 bits used used by aes the last 256 bits by the hmac.    additional context [source]( the realm file can be encrypted on disk by passing a 512-bit encryption key (64 bytes)  realm transparently encrypts and decrypts data with standard aes-256 encryption

Title_Description: the realm is already in a write transaction with unrelated executetransaction calls  goal  to report a potential issue between transactions and listener notifications.   expected results  to have multiple unrelated executetransaction calls in one thread (like the ui thread) without the risk of crashing due to realm already being writing a transaction.   actual results  i have 2 unrelated executetransaction calls in the same thread and due to a third transaction running in the background they crash.   steps   code to reproduce  i created a simplified android project to reproduce the issue (please disregard the concepts behind the objects in the project)   the idea of the test project - the objects 1xapp 1xsession and 10xitem - app and session are related to one another but unrelated to item - when app is updated it updates session - app is being updated in the background every 100ms which triggers a listener to update session - you can click on items in a list to toggle their isbookmarked property - if you click a few times eventually the application will crash because it will try to update session after starting a transaction to update an item. it will call notifychangelisteners after begintransaction - this is the issue   version of realm realm version(s) 4.3.4

Title_Description: add wrappers for new password provider methods we’ve added a few additional methods in ros that allow people to implement password reset and email confirmation flows. while these are simple http api it’d be nice to create wrappers for them. all of these rely on the idea that the username/password provider is actually used as email/password (which we probably have to highlight in the method docs).  the url for all actions is post   the body looks like    all return an empty response and will not provide indication if the user doesnt exist but will return errors if some of the parameters are invalid.  1. request password reset a reset password email is sent to the users email with some opaque token.     - provider_id is   required       - action is reset_password     -   no   other fields in data 2. confirm password reset after obtaining the token from the email the user can complete the password reset flow. by default ros will send an email that will redirect to  where a generic ui will be shown to complete the password reset. however its possible to override this url and e.g. change it to myapp//reset-password/ token  so that its handled by the app itself. its the developers responsibility to obtain the token if they want to complete the reset flow within the app.     - provider_id should not be provided     - action is complete_reset     - data contains the following additional fields         - token the token sent to the users email address.         - new_password the new password of the user. 3. initiate email confirmation for a lot of use cases people may want to know that the user has confirmed their email before allowing them to take certain actions in the app. an email will be sent to the users email address with an opaque token.     - provider_id is   required       - action is request_email_confirmation     -   no   other fields in data 4. confirm email similarly to the password reset flow the user obtains the token from the email somehow any must pass it to the server. by default well redirect to a generic page hosted in ros.     - provider_id should not be provided     - action is confirm_email     - data contains the following additional fields         - token the token sent to the users email address.     -   note   after the email is confirmed the json response after logging in with username/password will contain isemailconfirmed field set to true. we should probably surface that on the user object.  implementation/testing notes this depends on  being merged and released.
